=== START OF REFERENCE DOCUMENT WITH THE CORRECT INFO ===
    Generalizability attempt to evaluate a claim from McCarter_OrgBehavior_2010_pILK
Replication team: Kim Peters, University of Exeter
SCORE RR ID: 6ow46
OSF Project: https://osf.io/h7wx8/
Claim evaluation
Single-trace claim
Coded claim 4 text (original paper): Participants contributed significantly less toward the shared account in  losses-and-gains prospect conditions than in the no variance and gains-only prospect conditions; F(1,61) = 4.73, p < .05.
Replication outcome: Simple test
Inferential criteria: Support for H* will be indicated if b1<0, alpha =.05, two-tailed, indicating that the possibility of losses reduces contributions.
Result: The claim is tested with regression analysis with random intercepts for participant and group to account for the nesting of 4 threshold game contributions (each with a different bonus variance) within individuals, who are in turn nested within 8-person sessions. We found that the coefficient b1 (indicating the effect of the potential for losses in the bonus variance on contributions) is negative but not significant at the 5% level (b1=-0.5453125, se=0.9886449, p=.581).
Therefore, the claim is not replicated. 
Additional analyses
Exploratory analysis that repeats the above analysis for participants’ agreement with the item measuring their loss aversion found a marginally significant positive coefficient for losses at the 5% level (coefficient = 0.1344566, se=0.0730232, p=.066). Repeating this analysis for participants’ agreement with the item measuring their fear of non-contribution found a positive non-significant coefficient for losses at the 5% level (coefficient = 0.0414602, se=0.0586011, p=.479). 
General discussion 
This generalization finds that when participants can communicate ahead of contributing to a threshold public good there is no evidence that the possibility of losses decreases their willingness to contribute. Thus, the original findings do not appear to generalise to situations where people are able to communicate. The exploratory analysis provided weak evidence that the possibility of losses increased participants’ loss aversion, but there was no evidence that it increased their fear of non-contribution. 
Deviations from preregistration
We planned to collect data online from the University of Exeter FEELE participant pool and or the online survey platform Prolific. However, because of high dropout rates online, we collected the bulk of the data from FEELE participants in the lab. In line with lab rules, participants who turned up to an in-person session but could not participate were paid £5. 
To reduce the chance of dropouts when data was collected online, we created a Qualtrics survey that presented the consent form and then asked participants to indicate that they understand that (1) the study takes 25 minutes and are able to commit to completing it and (2) if they drop out before the session is complete the data from the session will not be usable, costing the experimenter time and money.  

